In C#, you can create a randomly generated maze using a depth-first search (DFS) algorithm along with a stack data structure. Here is the code for generating a randomly generated maze with customizable dimensions.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class MazeGenerator
{
    private static int width;
    private static int height;
    private static int[,] maze;
    private static Random random = new Random();

    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        width = 21;
        height = 21;
        maze = new int[height, width];
        GenerateMaze();
        PrintMaze();
    }

    private static void GenerateMaze()
    {
        for (int y = 0; y < height; y++)
            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++)
                maze[y, x] = (x % 2 == 0 || y % 2 == 0) ? 1 : 0;

        Stack<(int x, int y)> stack = new Stack<(int, int)>();
        stack.Push((1, 1));

        while (stack.Count > 0)
        {
            (int x, int y) = stack.Peek();
            maze[y, x] = 2;

            int[] dx = { -1, 1, 0, 0 };
            int[] dy = { 0, 0, -1, 1 };
            List<int> possibleDirections = new List<int>();

            for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++)
            {
                int nx = x + dx[i] * 2, ny = y + dy[i] * 2;
                if (nx > 0 && nx < width - 1 && ny > 0 && ny < height - 1 && maze[ny, nx] == 0)
                    possibleDirections.Add(i);
            }

            if (possibleDirections.Count == 0)
            {
                stack.Pop();
            }
            else
            {
                int nextDirection = possibleDirections[random.Next(possibleDirections.Count)];
                maze[y + dy[nextDirection], x + dx[nextDirection]] = 2;
                stack.Push((x + dx[nextDirection] * 2, y + dy[nextDirection] * 2));
            }
        }
    }

    private static void PrintMaze()
    {
        for (int y = 0; y < height; y++)
        {
            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++)
                Console.Write(maze[y, x] == 1 ? "##" : "  ");
            Console.WriteLine();
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, replace the `width` and `height` values in the `Main` method with the desired dimensions. Keep in mind that they should be odd numbers to ensure proper generation. This code will create a maze with a single path from the top left corner to the bottom right corner, and print it in the console.

One of the most simple algorithms for creating a maze is the "recursive backtracking" algorithm. Here's how it can be coded in C#:

1. Create a grid of cells. Each cell can have walls on each of its four sides (north, south, east, west).

```csharp
int width = 10;
int height = 10;
Cell[,] cells = new Cell[width, height];
for (int x = 0; x < width; x++)
{
  for (int y = 0; y < height; y++)
  {
    cells[x, y] = new Cell();
  }
}
```

2. Choose a starting cell and mark it as visited. 

```csharp
Cell current = cells[0, 0];
current.Visited = true;
```

3. While there are unvisited cells, choose a random unvisited neighbor of the current cell. If there are no unvisited neighbors, backtrack to the previous cell.

```csharp
while (!AllCellsVisited(cells))
{
  List<Cell> unvisitedNeighbors = GetUnvisitedNeighbors(cells, current);
  if (unvisitedNeighbors.Count > 0)
  {
    Cell chosen = unvisitedNeighbors[rand.Next(unvisitedNeighbors.Count)];
    RemoveWalls(current, chosen);
    chosen.Visited = true;
    stack.Push(current);
    current = chosen;
  }
  else if (stack.Count > 0)
  {
    current = stack.Pop();
  }
}
```

4. To remove walls between two cells, determine which direction the second cell is in, and remove the corresponding wall for both cells.

```csharp
private void RemoveWalls(Cell current, Cell chosen)
{
  int dx = current.X - chosen.X;
  int dy = current.Y - chosen.Y;
  if (dx == 1)
  {
    current.West = false;
    chosen.East = false;
  }
  else if (dx == -1)
  {
    current.East = false;
    chosen.West = false;
  }
  else if (dy == 1)
  {
    current.North = false;
    chosen.South = false;
  }
  else if (dy == -1)
  {
    current.South = false;
    chosen.North = false;
  }
}
```

5. To identify which cells are unvisited neighbors, check which cells are adjacent and unvisited.

```csharp
private List<Cell> GetUnvisitedNeighbors(Cell[,] cells, Cell current)
{
  List<Cell> neighbors = new List<Cell>();

  int x = current.X;
  int y = current.Y;

  if (x > 0 && !cells[x-1,y].Visited)
  {
    neighbors.Add(cells[x-1,y]);
  }
  if (x < cells.GetLength(0)-1 && !cells[x+1,y].Visited)
  {
    neighbors.Add(cells[x+1,y]);
  }
  if (y > 0 && !cells[x,y-1].Visited)
  {
    neighbors.Add(cells[x,y-1]);
  }
  if (y < cells.GetLength(1)-1 && !cells[x,y+1].Visited)
  {
    neighbors.Add(cells[x,y+1]);
  }

  return neighbors;
}
```

6. To check if all cells have been visited, iterate over all cells and check if they are visited.

```csharp
private bool AllCellsVisited(Cell[,] cells)
{
  for (int x = 0; x < cells.GetLength(0); x++)
  {
    for (int y = 0; y < cells.GetLength(1); y++)
    {
      if (!cells[x,y].Visited)
      {
        return false;
      }
    }
  }
  return true;
}
```

